 T HE whirling sledgehammer arches through the air and smashes into a giant telescreen that holds ranks of passive people captivated. Big Brother&#39;s monstrous face shatters into a brilliant shower of light and glass. Then comes the postscript: &#39;&#39;On January 24th, Apple Computer will introduce MacIntosh. And you will see why 1984 won&#39;t be like &#39;1984.&#39; &#39;&#39;
 In a striking departure from the direct, buy-this- product approach of most American corporations, Apple Computer introduced its new line of personal computers with the provocative claim that MacIntosh would help save the world from the lockstep society of George Orwell&#39;s novel. The message is notable in another sense, too. Like the more conventional magazine campaign begun several weeks ago by International Business Machines, the Apple commercial acknowledges that the potential for computer abuse is real.
 The advertisements appeared after a Harris poll, taken in September, found that Americans are increasingly concerned about privacy questions. At the time, the I.R.S. had begun testing the use of computerized life- style information, such as the types of cars people own, to track down errant taxpayers, while an F.B.I. advisory committee had recommended that the bureau computer system include data on people who, though not charged with wrongdoing, associate with drug traffickers.
 Apple&#39;s MacIntosh television spot, shown nationally during the Super Bowl game in January and on 10 local outlets, never stated its theme explicitly. But it grew out of an abandoned print campaign that did. &#39;&#39;True enough,&#39;&#39; reads one draft, &#39;&#39;there are monster computers lurking in big business and big government that know everything from what motels you&#39;ve stayed at to how much money you have in the bank. But at Apple we&#39;re trying to balance the scales by giving individuals the kind of computer power once reserved for corporations.&#39;&#39;
 &#39;&#39;The notion that a personal computer will set you free is appalling,&#39;&#39; said Joseph Weizenbaum, a computer science professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology. &#39;&#39;The ad seems to say the remedy to too much technology is more technology. It&#39;s like selling someone a pistol to defend himself in the event of nuclear war.&#39;&#39;
 Michael Tyler, a communications expert who works out of New York and London, was more sympathetic. &#39;&#39;The Apple ad expresses a potential of small computers,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;This potential may not automatically flow from the company&#39;s product. But if enough people held a shared intent, grass-roots electronic bulletin boards (through which computer users share messages) might result in better balancing of political power.&#39;&#39;
 Apple executives express delight with the presentation, which was filmed in England for about $370,000 by Ridley Scott, director of the movies &#39;&#39;Alien,&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;The Duelist&#39;&#39; and &#39;&#39;Blade Runner.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;After it ran we had hundreds of calls, 15 to 1 for it,&#39;&#39; said Dee MacLeod, product advertising manager for MacIntosh.
  Apple&#39;s suggestion that large computers, such as those manufactured by I.B.M., can threaten democratic values has been echoed in recent weeks - by I.B.M. Under a dramatic two-page, black and yellow drawing of the warning lines painted down the middle of a highway, the headline reads: &#39;&#39;There are rules for driving a computer, too.&#39;&#39; Chief among these: &#39;&#39;Everyone who uses a computer has a responsibility for the security of the information in that machine. No one who uses a computer has the right to violate anyone else&#39;s security.&#39;&#39;
 Harry DeMaio, the company&#39;s director for data security, said the advertisement was part of a broad campaign triggered by the increasing use of computers in homes, schools and small businesses. &#39;&#39;We are developing films, brochures aimed at increasing the awareness of this new constituency,&#39;&#39; Mr. DeMaio said. &#39;&#39;We&#39;re not trying to be arrogant or smug. The problems we&#39;re talking about can&#39;t be solved by technology alone. We wanted to ask churches, schools and other institutions of our society to start giving more thought to them.&#39;&#39;
 There seems to be an eager audience for the message. A film distribution company working with I.B.M. reported that last year, a nine-minute corporate film entitled &#39;&#39;Information: Handle With Care,&#39;&#39; was shown 3,260 times to 71,000 viewers. The film&#39;s producer said he had sold more than 800 copies.
 Dr. Weizenbaum believes one point underlies the two advertisements - &#39;&#39;computers represent a real threat requiring a real defense&#39;&#39; - and one motivation underlies the two campaigns. The companies, he said, &#39;&#39;know the spotlight soon will be on them and they want to have their position nailed down before they get caught.&#39;&#39;
 Brent Thomas, the art director at Chiat/Day in Los Angeles who helped create Apple&#39;s presentation, said the company had wanted something to &#39;&#39;stop America in its tracks, to make people think about computers, to make them think about MacIntosh.&#39;&#39; With about $3.5 million worth of MacIntoshes sold just after the advertisement ran, Mr. Thomas judged the effort &#39;&#39;absolutely successful.&#39;&#39; &#39;&#39;We also set out to smash the old canard that the computer will enslave us,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;We did not say the computer will set us free - I have no idea how it will work out. This was strictly a marketing position.&#39;&#39;
